and, Jones illustrates how Western legal thought has shaped the historical claims process. As Indigenous self-determination plays out on the world stage, this nuanced reflection brings into focus prospects for the long-term success of reconciliation projects in Canada and around the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLand tenure (Maori law). 0aLand tenure (Māori law) 0aMaori (New Zealand people)xClaims. 0aMaori (New Zealand people)xLand tenure. 0aMaori (New Zealand people)xLegal status, laws, etc. 0aMāori (New Zealand people)xClaims. 0aMāori (New Zealand people)xLand tenure. 0aMāori (New Zealand people)xLegal status, laws, etc. 0aReconciliation (Law)xNew Zealand. 0aReconciliation (Law)zNew Zealand. 7aHISTORY / Australia & New Zealand.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311141795040uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483170340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774831703423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774831703/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-141795-0  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles